Re: DIS: BUS: Notes on newly expensive Proposal passage

Blob wrote:

>David Albertz writes:
 
>> I don't think the fuss is about what it costs the proposer, but about
>> making it easy to get trivial but desireable proposals passed in spite of
>> Player reluctance to spend scarce votes.

>Few players would be reluctant to spend votes that you promise to give
>them, unless you are so untrustworthy. It doesn't take much to suggest to
>another player that you would give em a VT if e votes for your prop. If
>the proposal is uncontraversial, few players would be so ungenerous as to
>knock you back. If no-one else will, ask me. I will happily spend your 
>VTs to vote for your proposals, at no extra charge.

True, but why should anyone have to go through such machinations?  Make a
trivial proposal, spend one of your own votes, and be done with it.

-- Crito

